    },
    "body": "This PR make Quack Cross Entropy loss 'drop in ready' for PyTorch models.  It does this by adding:\r\n1 - options to reduce the cross entropy loss based on mean, sum, or none. \r\n\r\nCurrently the cross entropy returns a tensor of per example losses, but if you try and drop it into a PyTorch model and go, you will encounter:\r\n~~~\r\nRuntimeError: grad can be implicitly created only for scalar outputs\r\n~~~\r\n\r\nThis is because most people are calling loss.backward() expecting a scalar return value in their training loop. \r\n\r\nThis PR resolves that with the caveat that you still have to spec 'reduction = 'mean' when instantiating Quack CE within PyTorch, but now it's much easier to do.   \r\nNot sure if I should add a note in the comments about usage...\r\n\r\n#### Perf:\r\n\r\nWith that change, I tested on B200 and Llama3-8B, eager:\r\n<img width=\"370\" height=\"84\" alt=\"Screenshot 2025-07-16 at 3 45 18 PM\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/767b1eca-a867-484d-8f70-5ce1888ff8e0\" />\r\n\r\nNot much speedup, but a nice drop in Memory.  Note that combinining this with Quack RMSNorm and you get a meaningful **26.29%** drop in memory and speedup of **~12%**.  Thus, some synergy that is meaningful esp for memory.\r\n\r\n#### Testing:\r\nThe defaults are unchanged, and as expected, all cross entropy testing passes:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"1086\" height=\"129\" alt=\"Screenshot 2025-07-16 at 3 38 43 PM\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8a86e007-7ec2-42a3-a388-9efee0e280f6\" />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
